re centralisation claims: a) liquidity is more efficient decentralised due to more routes; b) the tech is built to support decentralisation, c) policy is automatically routed around by the software, d) transfers are atomic and trustless (in a periodic monitoring reactive model).

This also relates to optimising for delivered privacy. Privacy needs a big anonymity set "privacy loves company" so user interface, default on and simple to understand concept summary are important. More better crypto privacy with few users may deliver less privacy.

But you are right that simplified claims that make any current tech sound like a silver bullet are a problem. Best technologists can do is work with very technical journalists like @AaronvanW @kyletorpey and a few others with a track record of accurate tech reporting.

Sure but not an argument to not do LN as it is a clear scale & incremental privacy win. The last 5 years history on CT, indirectly leading to an R&D track that inspired research to bullet proofs shows that optimized, deployed incremental improvements beget more break-throughs.

The correct response is thank you and a bug bounty payment, and to learn lessons about Schneier's Law/risks of amateurs rolling their own crypto. Implausible/unfundable via experienced investors plans, ICO craziness and promoter boosterism are whole other issues.

Plus in a world which benefits from pseudonyms how do we know who entered when? As you say who cares - it is a meritocracy. Number of coins is not always correlated - spent coins, no money as a student to buy coins etc. Most are motivated by the socio-technical change potential.

LN improves privacy with backward-secure & anonymous onion tunnels. To observe you need to be in the channel which is an active attack. Nothing is perfect at present including trusted setup, with novel crypto assumptions and possible crypto fail inflation risk, most tx unshielded

14/ Last note, excessive use of snark detracts from the credibility of any argument, and is a waste of time for the reader. @BKoral_Austere and @anshumanaustere would do well to learn this if they want Austere Capital to be taken seriously.

13/ Many of the summaries of how I approach things are wrong (especially the below image), and I don’t appreciate having words put in my mouth. PQ is divided by V, to get M. PQ is *not* divided by M, & networks have asset flows, *not* revenues, as I have stated time & again pic.twitter.com/rl1d4yWcLZ

12/ Circularity claim also mixes present & future. The M that matters & therefore token value that matters, is based on future expectations, which are discounted back. Part of this present value is supported by current demand 4 the token, but that's not how the token is priced

11/ Austere’s circularity claim appears misplaced and is confusing to follow. Necessary monetary base, M, is solved by PQ / V, with the price of the token as a derivative of that M and *never* used as an input (which Austere claims). pic.twitter.com/YbiHL61IRS
10/ Everything is priced in dollars (i.e., the world’s reserve currency), so saying an equation to price cryptoassets can’t use dollars is nonsensical.
9/ Then, the claim that you can’t use USD in MV = PQ to back out a necessary M value in USD for a token is unfounded — authors just say you “cannot” do it with no explanation.

8/ As @alexhevans has pointed out to me, MV = PQ can be thought of as Money Supplied = Money Demanded. Perhaps this can get away from clinging to how MV = PQ has been used in the past. Also worth noting how MV = PQ has been used over the last century has morphed considerably.

7/ First, claiming you can’t use an identity outside of “its original context and constraints” doesn’t make any sense. So long as you understand your assumptions, an identity is an identity and the math works for whatever variable you solve for.

6/ Since I’m getting questions about the aforementioned article from Austere Capital in particular, to follow are my thoughts. Happy to be proven wrong on these, to the benefit of crypto, with more robust proof.

5/ Secondly, MV = PQ leaves out the “trading economy," which I did purposefully but nonetheless ignores a large part of what drives the value of these assets currently. Yet, given the speculative and largely irrational nature of the trading economy I’m not sure it can be modeled

4/ For me, the major constraint of MV = PQ is there are many moving parts & as of yet poorly understood assumptions that go into V, P, & Q to back out M. That said, DCF’s have a similarly large #of assumptions, they have just been refined over decades (arguably centuries).

3/ The piece does, however, set the stage for conversation around better equations, or more rigorous arguments around flaws in applying MV = PQ in this way, which I’d love to hear more of, and have mentioned before: https:// twitter.com/cburniske/stat us/952625373614870534 … pic.twitter.com/a3jhuy81By

2/ While the below article claims to debunk MV = PQ, none of its arguments particularly concern me as the Achilles heel of the Equation of Exchange in its use to value cryptoassets: https:// medium.com/@AustereCapita l/mv-p-que-love-and-circularity-in-the-time-of-crypto-1626c8ac297f …
1/ I’ve been thinking & reading history about MV = PQ a lot, and what other models would be more suitable for valuing cryptoassets and why.

But the Heller ruling explicitly stated the government could regulate commercial firearm transactions, restrict ownership by felons or mentally ill, and ban private ownership of particularly dangerous or unusual weapons (e.g., bazookas).
Heller (2008) was seen as a huge victory for the NRA because it recognized historic 2A right the bear arms privately, for self-defense, unconnected to militia service.
